       <div class="page-header">
        <h1> <a href="/java-core/tools/how-to-compile-package-and-run-a-java-program-using-command-line-tools-javac-jar-and-java"> How to compile, package and run a Java program using command-line tools (javac, jar and java)</a></h1>
       </div>
       <div class="article-info muted">
        <dl class="article-info">
         <dt class="article-info-term">
          Details
         </dt>
         <dd class="modified"> 
          <span class="icon-calendar"></span> Last Updated on 19 July 2016 &nbsp; | &nbsp; 
          <a href="/java-core/tools/how-to-compile-package-and-run-a-java-program-using-command-line-tools-javac-jar-and-java?tmpl=component&amp;print=1&amp;page=" title="Print" onclick="window.open(this.href,'win2','status=no,toolbar=no,scrollbars=yes,titlebar=no,menubar=no,resizable=yes,width=640,height=480,directories=no,location=no'); return false;" rel="nofollow"><span class="icon-print"></span>&nbsp;Print&nbsp;</a> 
          <a href="/component/mailto/?tmpl=component&amp;template=protostar&amp;link=54695c6a605ae3f5c1a1b6318788878601c396da" title="Email" onclick="window.open(this.href,'win2','width=400,height=350,menubar=yes,resizable=yes'); return false;"><span class="icon-envelope"></span> Email</a>
         </dd>
        </dl>
       </div>
       <div>
        <a href="https://click.linksynergy.com/link?id=d1Fh24*EiQI&amp;offerid=323058.1344876&amp;type=2&amp;murl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.udemy.com%2Fwhats-new-in-java-9%2F?couponCode=OPENING&amp;u1=Java9" target="_blank" rel="nofllow"><b><font size="+1" color="red">NEW COURSE: </font><font size="+1" color="black">What's New In Java 9</font></b></a>
       </div>This tutorial helps you use the core tools in JDK (
       <span style="color: #800000;"><strong><span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">javac</span></strong></span>, 
       <span style="color: #800000;"><strong><span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">jar</span></strong> </span>and 
       <span style="color: #800000;"><strong><span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">java</span></strong></span>) to compile, package and run a Java program under the following circumstance:
       <p></p>
       <p style="margin-left: 30px;">- The Java source file is under a package.</p>
       <p style="margin-left: 30px;">- There’s an external library.</p>
       <p style="margin-left: 30px;">- The JAR file is an executable JAR.</p> By following this tutorial step by step, you will be able to use the three tools (
       <strong><span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">javac</span></strong>, 
       <strong><span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">jar</span></strong> and 
       <strong><span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">java</span></strong>) together fluently in your daily Java programming.
       <p></p> The Java program we use in this tutorial is a JDBC client that connects to a MySQL database named 
       <strong>Students</strong> and inserts a row into the table 
       <i>students</i>. Here’s the MySQL script to create the database:
       <p></p>
       <pre class="brush:text">create database Students;
use Students;

CREATE TABLE `student` (
  `student_id` int(11) NOT NULL,
  `name` varchar(45) NOT NULL,
  `email` varchar(45) NOT NULL,
  `university` varchar(45) NOT NULL,
  PRIMARY KEY (`student_id`),
  UNIQUE KEY `student_id_UNIQUE` (`student_id`)
) ENGINE=InnoDB DEFAULT CHARSET=latin1</pre>You need to download the 
       <a href="/java-se/jdbc/connect-to-mysql-database-via-jdbc" target="_blank">JDBC driver library for MySQL</a> in order to run the program.
       <p></p> &nbsp;
       <p></p>
       <h1><strong><span style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;">1. Organizing Directories Structure</span></strong></h1> Create the following director structure on your computer:
       <p></p> 
       <img style="display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;" src="/images/articles/javacore/tools/javac-jar-java/directory_structure.png" alt="directory structure" width="220" height="171">
       <p></p> The way you organize files is very important, as it affects the readability, maintainability and extensibility of a program when it evolves over times. Therefore it’s recommended to follow a common, standard directory structure as shown in the screenshot above. Let’s understand each directory in details:
       <p></p>
       <ul>
        <li><span style="color: #800000;"><strong><span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">classes</span></strong></span>: contain compiled classes (<span style="font-size: 10pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: 'Courier New';">.class</span> files)</li>
        <li><span style="color: #800000;"><strong>l</strong><strong><span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">i</span>b</strong></span>: contains third-party libraries. Here is MySQL Connector JAR file.</li>
        <li><span style="color: #800000;"><strong><span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">src</span></strong></span>: contains source code which is organized in sub directories representing Java packages. Here’s the package is <span style="font-size: 10pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: 'Courier New'; color: #800000;">net.codejava </span>and the Java source file is <span style="font-size: 10pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: 'Courier New'; color: #800000;">StudentsInsert.java</span>.</li>
       </ul> And below is source code of the program in the 
       <span style="font-size: 10pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: 'Courier New';">StudentsInsert.java</span> file:
       <p></p>
       <pre class="brush:java">package net.codejava;

import org.apache.log4j.BasicConfigurator;
import org.apache.log4j.Logger;


import java.io.BufferedReader;
import java.io.InputStreamReader;
import java.sql.Connection;
import java.sql.DriverManager;
import java.sql.PreparedStatement;
import java.util.Scanner;

/**
 *
 * A JDBC client program that inserts a row into a MySQL database.
 * @author www.codejava.net
 */
public class StudentsInsert {

	@SuppressWarnings("resource")
	public static void main(String[] args) {

		// Initialising database and connection objects:
		String dbURL = "jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/Students";
		String username = "root";
		String password = "P@ssw0rd";

		Connection conn = null;
		String sql = null;

		try {

			Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);
			System.out.print("Enter the number of students: ");

			int numberOfStudents = scanner.nextInt();
			int countInsertion = 0;
			int countInformationToDisplay = 1;

			BufferedReader reader = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in));

			while (countInsertion &lt; numberOfStudents) {
				System.out.println("Enter information for student #" + countInformationToDisplay + "\t");
				System.out.print("");
				System.out.print("\tName: ");
				String name = reader.readLine();
				System.out.print("\tEmail: ");
				String email = reader.readLine();
				System.out.print("\tUniversity: ");
				String university = reader.readLine();

				conn = DriverManager.getConnection(dbURL, username, password);

				// Inserting data to the Student table
				sql = "INSERT INTO Student (name, email, university) VALUES (?, ?, ?)";
				PreparedStatement statement = conn.prepareStatement(sql);
				statement.setString(1, name);
				statement.setString(2, email);
				statement.setString(3, university);

				int rowInserted = statement.executeUpdate();

				if (rowInserted &gt; 0) {
					++countInsertion;
					++countInformationToDisplay;
				}

				System.out.println("" + countInsertion + " students saved to database.");
			}
		} catch (Exception ex) {
			ex.printStackTrace();
		} finally {
			try {
				if (conn != null) {
					conn.close();
				}
			} catch (Exception ex) {
				ex.printStackTrace();
			}
		}
	}
}</pre>

       </div>Now, let’s see how to compile, create JAR and run this program using command line tools
       <p></p> &nbsp;
       <p></p>
       <h1><strong><span style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;">2. Compile the program using javac command</span></strong></h1> Open command prompt and move the current directory to the 
       <span style="font-size: 10pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: 'Courier New';">StudentProgram</span>.
       <p></p>
       <p style="text-indent: 0.5in;"><span style="color: #800000;"><strong><span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">javac -d classes src\net\codejava\StudentsInsert.java</span></strong></span></p> This command compiles the 
       <span style="font-size: 10pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: 'Courier New'; color: #800000;">StudentsInsert.java </span>source file and places the 
       <span style="font-size: 10pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: 'Courier New';">.class</span> files under the 
       <span style="font-size: 10pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: 'Courier New'; color: #800000;">classes </span>directory. The 
       <span style="font-size: 10pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: 'Courier New'; color: #800000;">-d </span>option is used to specify the output directory containing compiled files. A good thing is that, the Java compiler automatically creates package directories structure in the destination directory, as shown in the following screenshot:
       <p></p> 
       <img style="display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;" src="/images/articles/javacore/tools/javac-jar-java/compiled_files_directory.png" alt="compiled files directory" width="200" height="157">
       <p></p> In case the source files reference third-party library (JAR) files, use the 
       <strong><span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">-cp</span></strong> option and specify the JAR file. For example:
       <p></p>
       <p style="margin-left: 0.5in;"><span style="color: #800000;"><strong><span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">javac -cp lib\mysql-connector-java-5.1.21-bin.jar -d classes src\net\codejava\StudentsInsert.java</span></strong></span></p> If there are multiple JAR files, they must be separated by semicolon like this:
       <p></p>
       <p style="margin-left: 0.5in;"><span style="color: #800000;"><strong><span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">javac -cp lib\mysql-connector-java-5.1.21-bin.jar;lib\log4j-1.2.17.jar -d classes src\net\codejava\StudentsInsert.java</span></strong></span></p>
       <p style="margin-left: 0.5in;">&nbsp;</p>
       <h1><strong><span style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;">3. Create executable JAR file using jar command</span></strong></h1> Before wrapping the compiled files into an executable JAR file, let create 
       <span style="font-size: 10pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: 'Courier New'; color: #800000;">manifest.txt</span> file (using a simple text editor such as Notepad on Windows or Vi on Linux) in the current directory (
       <span style="font-size: 10pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: 'Courier New';">StudentProgram</span>) with the following content:
       <p></p>
       <p style="margin-left: 0.5in;"><span style="font-size: 9pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: 'Courier New';">Main-Class: net.codejava.StudentsInsert</span></p>
       <p style="margin-left: 0.5in;"><span style="font-size: 9pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: 'Courier New';">Class-Path: lib\mysql-connector-java-5.1.21-bin.jar</span></p>
       <p style="margin-left: 0.5in;"><span style="font-size: 9pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: 'Courier New';">&lt;blank line&gt;</span></p> The first line specifies the class will be called when the JAR file gets executed. This class must have 
       <span style="font-size: 10pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: 'Courier New'; color: #800000;">main()</span> method. You see the 
       <span style="font-size: 10pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: 'Courier New'; color: #800000;">StudentsInsert </span>class is specified with its fully qualified name (including package name).
       <p></p> The second line specifies the third-party libraries referenced by the program. Here we specify the MySQL Connector library JAR file. In case you refer multiple JAR files, separate them by spaces like this:
       <p></p>
       <p style="text-indent: 0.5in;"><span style="font-size: 10pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: 'Courier New'; color: #800000;">Class-Path: lib\mysql-connector-java-5.1.21-bin.jar lib\log4j-1.2.17.jar</span></p> Here we specify the paths relative to the JAR file being created.
       <p></p> &nbsp;
       <p></p> 
       <strong><span style="font-size: 12pt; line-height: 115%;">NOTE:</span></strong> There must be a blank line at the end of the manifest file, otherwise it won’t work.
       <p></p> Now type the following command to package the JAR file:
       <p></p>
       <p style="text-indent: 0.5in;"><span style="color: #800000;"><strong><span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">jar cfm StudentsInsert.jar manifest.txt -C classes net</span></strong></span></p> The 
       <strong><span style="font-family: 'Courier New';"><span style="color: #800000;">c</span> </span></strong>option is for creating a JAR file.
       <p></p> The
       <strong><span style="font-family: 'Courier New';"><span style="color: #800000;"> f</span> </span></strong>option specifies the JAR file name.
       <p></p> The 
       <span style="color: #800000;"><strong><span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">m</span></strong> </span>option specifies where to look at the manifest file.
       <p></p> The 
       <strong><span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">-<span style="color: #800000;">C</span></span></strong> option specifies where to take the 
       <span style="font-size: 10pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: 'Courier New';">.class</span> files. Here we specify the entire package in the 
       <span style="font-size: 10pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: 'Courier New'; color: #800000;">classes </span>directory.
       <p></p> 
       <span style="font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: 'Calibri','sans-serif';">You should see the </span>
       <span style="font-size: 10pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: 'Courier New'; color: #800000;">StudentsInsert.jar</span>
       <span style="font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: 'Calibri','sans-serif';"> file created. The whole directory structure would look like this:</span>
       <p></p> 
       <span style="font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: 'Calibri','sans-serif';"><img style="display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;" src="/images/articles/javacore/tools/javac-jar-java/final_directory_structure.png" alt="final directory structure" width="330" height="283"></span>
       <p></p> 
       <strong><span style="font-size: 12pt; line-height: 115%;">NOTE:</span></strong> If the JAR file doesn’t depend on any third-part libraries, we don’t have to create the manifest file. Instead, we can use the 
       <strong>e</strong> option to specify the main class.
       <p></p> &nbsp;
       <p></p>
       <h1><strong><span style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;">4. Run the program using java command</span></strong></h1> Now type the following command to execute the newly generated JAR file:
       <p></p>
       <p style="text-indent: 0.5in;"><span style="color: #800000;"><strong><span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">java -jar StudentsInsert.jar</span></strong></span></p> Enter the inputs when requested. The following screenshot depicts the running of this program:
       <p></p> 
       <img style="display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;" src="/images/articles/javacore/tools/javac-jar-java/command_prompt.png" alt="command prompt" width="260" height="154">
       <p></p> We hope you find this tutorial helpful for your Java development using command line tools. You can download the whole project under the Attachments section to experiment yourself.
       <p></p>
